<TITLE> Stocks open week downbeat </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sep 14 (bdnews24.com) A selling spree caused markets to maintain losses on the opening day of the week. Profit taking caused more than 70 percent of traded scrips to fall, while blue chip shares on the country's twin bourses declined sharply. The Dhaka Stock Exchange started the day in a slump before midday buying pushed indices up to end almost flat. The benchmark DGEN or general index fell 1.99 points or 0.69 percent, finishing at 2848.17. The DSI or all-share price index ended on 2405.85, slipping 0.85 points or 0.03 percent. The blue chip DSE-20 declined 16.17 points, or 0.66 percent, to close at 2426.10. Huge losses in non-bank financial institutions, pharmaceuticals and banks along with the blue chips caused indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange to finish downbeat. The CSCX or selective categories index closed 20.52 points or 0.23 percent lower at 5695.42. The CASPI or all-share price index finished at 8718.89, falling 20.59 points or 0.23 percent. The bourse's blue chip CSE-30 slumped 53.98 points or 0.69 percent to close on 7735.55. Turnover on the DSE reached at Tk 2.72 billionwith 21,247,548 shares changing handswhile the port city bourse saw 4,425,894 shares traded with a turnover of Tk 406.704 million. Losers outshined gainers on the DSE by 160 to 50, while 18 issues held steady. On the CSE, 100 issues lost, 30 gained and four remained unchanged. Top in turnover on the DSE, Titas Gas gained 4.04 percent to Tk 494.75. Beximco finished at Tk 149.90, rising 13.73 percent. Grameen One: Scheme 2 continued to end on Tk 51.20, edging up 0.19 percent.. ACI slipped 0.15 percent to Tk 525.70 following last week's gains. ICB AMCL 2nd NRB Mutual Fund advanced 1.44 percent to Tk 228.75. Among the other scrips on the turnover board, Lanka Bangla Finance, AIMS 1st Mutual Fund, Union Capitals and Beximco Pharmaceuticals fell due to selling pressure. National Tubes gained. bdn
